Yearning for clarity of mind, I retrace my foot steps back to where I came from and find myself here - highly functional second life materials reborn in a performance oriented chefs knife. ✨ 

This knife is hand forged from century+ old carbon steel from a lumber mill saw blade I got from a farmer in Monticello, GA. The classic full tang construction is balanced by a tapered tang and spine to center the mass just in front of the handle. My freehand convex bevel geometry supports a robust, workhorse feel while the rounded choil and spine further energize the overall feel. 

The supple handle is sculpted from rejected African Blackwood from a Paris, France clarinet factory. Facets at the top aid in indexing while the uniform and symmetrical curved bottom 2/3rds make it comfortable. 

Whoever’s tree this is under is a lucky person. 🎄

After hurricane Irma, this oak burl was collected off the streets of Atlanta before being milled, cured, stabilized, shaped and finished on its way to its second life. 

I used century+ old carbon steel from an older middle Georgia farmer who gave me three saw blades off his family’s old home place.

It’s a joy to honor these materials and their past.

💫✨STARGAZER✨💫

Taking a second to get back to some basics opened up a small facet of my habitual brain for playfulness. If enjoying my work isn’t a priority, what’s the point? 

For my latest small group of work, I intentionally limited myself to a few key materials and build styles, focusing on forging and finish while utilizing as many recycled materials as possible. This tricked me into thinking it was more simple, and some extra bandwidth freed up to consider approaches outside of the current box I’ve built around myself. 

Enjoying the simple pleasures and hope you are too.

✨swamp magic ✨

Under this canopy in north Florida is a special place - spending decades here before moving to Athens GA and Jonesborough TN, I got my time swinging a hammer 40 hours a week, rain or shine, summer or winter under the comforting embrace of the live oaks. They offered protection from the elements, a constant reminder of the intimate relationship we humans have with our surroundings. 

Surround yourself with love and love your surroundings.
I can hear the traffic resonating up the hill from my shop - a sure sign that the world has officially returned to the rat race.  Here’s to taking time to slow down and enjoy the peace and quiet.

✨ An update on the @_cmckenna_  @lilliesq bourbon barrel strap suminagashi set ✨ I spent the week finishing these blades - which really feels like getting past the halfway point. I’m moving along more slowly than expected but my energy and excitement surrounding the material remains high! I love the function and aesthetics of this laminated steel, using soft materials as the cladding allows the high carbon steel core to be tempered harder. The pure nickel and bourbon barrel straps (the damascus looking cladding) always wear nicely into their patinas and the imported 26C3 carbon steel (which makes up the middle of these blades) is a most enjoyable steel to use in the kitchen.
I can’t get enough of this cherry burl, gifted to me by friends near Athens, GA - a place I remember fondly. I also love how a little heat enhances the color of this wood.
Just finished up this set for @_cmckenna_ the mastermind behind @lilliesq. Thanks for your patience and support - it was a pleasure to get to make these for you.

The Origin Collection: layers of bourbon barrel strap are cut, cleaned and fused together with pure nickel using fire, hammer and anvil.  Becoming one before being fused again to high performance carbon steel - this process of recycling not only allows me to put to use discarded materials, it means I can use smaller amounts of virgin material for the cutting edge. There is something inherently fulfilling in this amalgamation, turning old into new. The soft exterior protects the hard steel used for the edge. 

When studying human history, archaeologist dig through our physical remains - assuming and concluding based on what they find, based on what people left behind and what was important to them. They can tell which resources were valued and a society lived. This concept has been with me before I ever made a knife. What mark is my work leaving for future generations? What am i passing down? What will remain when I am dead? Did i rely on virgin materials? Or did I do as those before me and use what I've got to make what I need? This is my internal dialog.

Social media usually makes me feel worse than before i flicked it open. It can be toxic. I often find myself feeling like I’m not enough. i’m not dedicated enough. i'm not growing. I’m not doing enough.

Today i took a trip down memory lane and it opened my eyes. i saw my growth as a knife maker plain as day. each knife brought with it its own flood of memories surrounding the build and what it meant to me and what was going on in life when I made it. maybe it's not social media but actually just my mindset that is toxic. i've never wanted to be working on something else. when a knife is in process in my shop, it's all i can focus on. it's not easy to change gears but as soon as I acknowledge how grateful I am for where I am and all that I have, everything changes. Immediately. 

Here's your reminder that you're doing great.

One of my favorite materials to make and use is this laminated steel made with bourbon barrel straps. The pattern develops through the forging process and the outside layers remains soft through the hardening process which adds strength and protection to the hard high carbon core where the shaving sharp edge lives. Looking for a fillet or trimming knife? I’ve made a handful of these in my Heritage collection - a well made, simple build that utilizes reclaimed materials. In this case, the blade is forged from century+ old lumber mill saw carbon steel. Very pure, old steel that’s been lab tested and identified with specific heat treating based on the alloy and intended purpose.

The full tang handle is sculpted from stabilized oak burl that came down in hurricane Irma’s devastation in 2017. Harvested from the streets of Atlanta, milled, dried and professionally stabilized by @knifeandgunfinishingsupplies 

This and all Heritage Collection blades feature full distal tapers (the tang and spine are tapered for centered balance and agile hand feel) and silky smooth hand finishes on the blades. Rounded and polished spine adds to the comfort. They are ground freehand without the use of jigs to a very effective convex geometry and each blade is sharpened using whet stones. 

Vibrating with energy of their past, these materials have been hibernating for years, and it’s an honor to bring them back to life.

The Heritage collection of blades is where storied materials and elegant finishes come together. The reclaimed carbon steel is lab tested before being hand forged. The sturdy full tang construction is balanced with a gentle taper. The hand feel is enhanced by a silky smooth hand-polished blade and a rounded, comfortable spine.

SOLD

Heat treating (day 3!)

After forging a blade, the crystal structure inside the steel is all sorts of messed up, misaligned, different sizes… the result of heating different parts of a blade and pounding them. Forging is fun but it requires a little extra refinement during heat treating. 

The process of heat treating involves making this structure uniform in size and shrinking the structure size. This makes for a finer and more durable edge. After normalizing that structure, it’s time to take advantage of all that carbon inside the steel. Known as the critical temperature, once the steel is heated to this point, the crystals change to face centered, meaning the carbon atom migrates to the middle of the structure where there was once an iron atom. This is called austenite. Quenching quickly freezes the structure as is, trapping the carbon atoms and creating a really hard, brittle structure known as martensite.

Tempering afterwards decreases the hardness and brittleness while increasing toughness, envying each blade with functional hardness! 

I’ve never loved science, and though I find all of this fascinating, I still kind of prefer the more brief explanation of “it’s magic!”

I may always be enamored with this seemingly inconsequential portion of the process. After removing the protective layer after shaping the handle, is the first holistic look at the knife as a cohesive object. A definite moment of truth as Insee how far from my target I landed.

I’ve always loved objects that connect me with another human or a time and place. It’s my natural longing for connection, to belong to something larger than myself, a universal community that I want to exist. My works are bids for connection and coming from within, they represent a part of me. I keep hearing my 7th grade earth science teacher, Mr. Brown's voice in my head, "You better love whatever you do to make a living because you’re going to do a lot of it" It's echoed since he said it. And while there's an ebb and flow to the relationship I have with knife making and craft, I am always trying to become a better lover of what I do. Taking time off to learn something new feels like a huge luxury but it's something I owe to my craft. I think we all want to continue to grow and keep the magic alive by expanding our minds, skills and competencies. Time itself is the ultimate resource to accomplish this. Sometimes you need a week or two to try new things, fuck it all up, throw it all out and start to learn. Or in the case of these new little blades, start forging shapes you like for 30 minutes here and there while things are heating up or cooling down in the shop. Throw them to the side and forget about them for a couple years. Find them again and finish one. Forge a couple more. Finish another. Make four. Make four more. This is growth. It's slow, but it's good. And branching out from kitchen cutlery after about ten years has both been terrifying yet a natural feeling. 

This literal pile of knives plus a whole pile more will be showing up in subscribers' inboxes on Monday August 7th and I cannot wait to share more about these EDCs all dressed up in their leather from @bud_siniard.

Knives of Summer: Balance. As in work/life. Trying to be present for my family as well as my work. I identify as a simple person, but I do have facets that need attention from time to time. I ask a lot from the work I offer each season - making ends meet as well as ultimate creative fulfillment and endless personal growth. Running a business does not often leave room for all of these though I keep asking it to provide me with the perfect mix.

It seems completely ridiculous to promote a shop update right now, when the situation is dire for so many others. My house did not just burn down nor am I desperately searching for my wife and baby in a town reduced to ashes (as my sister's co-worker was last week). My sister moved to Maui a little over a year ago and I texted asking her what the point of driving to Lahaina was.  I heard it was closed. She replies "We are looking for people to help and dropping supplies." I ask, "what can we ship that is needed?" She replies, "diapers, hygiene items, baby items..." - as soon as I read that, I think back to only 5 minutes before when I was day dreaming about all the gifts I wanted to purchase my daughter, who is turning two soon.  She texts again, "and now we're taking in a family up stairs!" and I come to the realization that what is deemed essential is dependent on privilege - it's truly a sliding scale. At the most basic level, we need to survive before we can think of other comforts. I think of how spending the night with total strangers would be an excruciatingly uncomfortable experience and how it might feel to know that the clothes on my back are more than my neighbors escaped with. Hey Instagram. I’m Will, the knife maker here. I also pack, ship  and do most of the computer work… It's been a while since I've said much about myself so it’s time I introduce myself if we haven’t met.

I came to knife making through blacksmithing and I love to incorporate the process of forging recycled materials as often as possible because it’s a fun way to get where I want to go. I love making tools that surround the act of eating, not only sustaining life and spending time with friends and family, but enjoying food for how it makes your feel. 

I've been living in Tennessee's oldest town (@jonesborough) for five years before that my wife, dogs and I lived in the woods, outside of Athens, GA for 6 years. Prior to that I lived in Tallahassee, FL where I met @lcarella whose cooking continues to be my biggest muse for making kitchen knives. We now have a two year old daughter who consumes the moments between everything. 

Taking advice from my 7th grade science teacher, I’ve been chasing the ideal of loving what I do for a living and is a major reason I’m here now. The other major factors have involved mentors, past employment, art school and support from loved ones. 

Before going full time with knife making, I was a backyard knife maker, drummer and freelance audio engineer - editing film sound & recording some of my favorite bands including @dude____the_obscure @bandofhorses @amandapearlshires @kishi_bashi @drivebytruckers @alessisark and a ton of other super talented artists.

A year ago we hiked up from our raft to the Nankoweap Granaries built and used by Native Americans from the Ancestral Puebloan culture nearly 1000 years ago. Sealed airtight, they were used for storage of food and seed. As we approached, I couldn’t imagine hauling my harvest up that treacherous cliff hike each season. Looking down, I pondered the beauty of the Colorado River below, one of the most controlled, regulated and exploited rivers in the world and how it was home to 30 fish species found nowhere else, half of which extinct or at risk. The demand on the Colorado River Basin has continued to grow (serving 40 million people, including the large western cities: Los Angeles, Phoenix, Denver, Las Vegas) while we continue to ignore the fact that this resource can no longer support us. Is it too late to take a few steps back? Maybe it’s time to build some granaries of our own.
One for the field and one for the kitchen, I love a sensible set.

I rarely (if ever) finish a piece that I am satisfied with on all the levels. It seems like each finished knife informs the next. I am always striving, leaning in and getting humbled. As much as I try to improve my skills, im beginning to understand that the real challenge is learning how to look at my work more critically during the process. Learning when to recognize what will later bother me. The idea of becoming more skilled feels more like a mind set shift and is an ever evolving situation.

Restocked some supplies for the coming year. These are the abrasive belts I use for shaping steel after the forging process. It’s a constant source of internal conflict for me. I have found joy in aspects of grinding but am generally considering of ways to decrease the time I stand in front of my grinder. The longer I do it, the more second nature it becomes, but my favorite way to shape steel always has been and always will be with fire, hammer and anvil.
